title: For Sale:  Westinghouse Model 91 Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
This Westinghouse Model 91 Mosin Nagant rifle is in very good condition for its age.  This rifle is complete with sling and cleaning rod. This rifle has a matching bolt and the bore is good with light frosting, but good strong rifling.  This rifle was made in 1915 and was one of the few that was actually shipped to Russia.  It is Finnish Capture marked [SA].  This means this rifle was shipped to Russian from the US, used in the winter war against Finland, captured by the Fins and then shipped back to the US as a commercial import.

title: For Sale:  MARLIN CAMP  9mm Carbine (As New)
location: SW Miss, Pike, Licoln, Amite, Walthal, Mississippi, United States
postcontent:
These guns were discountinued by Marlin in 1999 and are hard to find-especially in this condition.
 I'm the only owner of this one. In 1991 there were only two 9mm carbines widely commercialy available, and even those were fairly scarce. I managed to find both in about two months time. I bought this Marlin, spent a range day with it. It fed all types of 9mm ammo, out of several boxes and proved to be quite acurate and stone reliable. The total round count would be
 between 75-125 rounds. I cleaned it, put it in a safe, and made plans to trick it out. A short time later I stumbled onto the other carbine of the day, and it shared controls with my taget rifle. In all honesty this Marlin has been well maintained but has not been shooting since.

The Camp 9 has a 16 1/2 micro groove barrel (12 groove), open sights and a high visibility orange front sight post with cutaway hood. Steel receiver is drilled and tapped for a scope. Overall length is 35 1/2 inches, and it weighs 6 3/4 lbs. WHile a note on the manuel states' Now available with 4rd hunting magazine it did not come with one. has a detachable 12 shot magazine. The carbine is compatible with Smith & Wesson 59 -5906 series handgun magazines.

This carbine is in near perfect condition. There is a very small light spot on the edge of the stock just above the trigger that came with it new. It may have rubbed something or the finish may be thin, there is no damage to the wood. Beyond that the metal and wood are flawless. Bore is mirror bright with sharp riflings. Thers is It is "as new" and includes, an additional 15 round magazine, and two megar 20rd magazines, and one Safariland Mag Loader,the factory manuel and it does come with the factory box, although the carbine was stored in a safe and the box was cramed in closet so the box has seen better days.
 The prices on these rifles range from ok for fairly rough ones, to ridiculous for nice ones. I'm asking $550.00 and I dont think you will find one in this shape within 200.00 of the price. Thanks for looking. Available in the SW  MS. area, Pike, Lincoln, Walthall counties.
Very few trades I would consider on this one, if any.

title: For Sale:  S&W 4506-1 45 ACP with ammo and extras
postcontent:
The S&W 4506 is one of the most reliable and durable automatic pistols ever made, more so than a Glock.  These pistols will chamber and fire ANY .45 ACP ammo, from widemouthed hollowpoints, to +P+ hardcast reloads, to dirty steel cased stuff, to powderpuff wadcutters . . . even primed cases.  These guns run forever, thousands of rounds with no jams even if left uncleaned, no breakage after 20,000+ rounds.  These are built on the same frame as the 1006 10mm, which has twice the power of 45 so you will not break this.  The 4506 is widely considered to be the best of the 3rd Generation S&W automatics.  Very soft shooting, with light recoil and outstanding accuracy.  Full sized (5" barrel) stainless steel pistol with blued Novak sights, trigger, and hammer (not MIM).  DA/SA with decocker.  8+1 capacity.  Single stack is good for shooters with smaller hands.

This was my Dad's gun, purchased new (not a police trade in), and was kept in his nightstand for 20 years.  Excellent condition with only a few faint handling marks.  Very low round count, under 500 rounds of brass cased ball.  Only modification was the sights were touched up with a bit of Hi-Viz paint, but that is easily removed with a little acetone if you don't like it.  Same style of pistol Vic Mackey used in "The Shield."

Smith & Wesson 4506-1 comes with 2 factory mags, a nice gun case, a 50 rd box of new Winchester Ranger T-series Law Enforcement +P ammo, and a 25 rd box of Remington Golden Saber +P ammo.  The ammo alone is worth over a hundred bucks, and I'm throwing it in for free as I have no other guns in this caliber.  Do not have the original box or manual, but the instructions are available online as a pdf and detailed field strip videos can be found on youtube.  If you want rubber or wood grips, Hogue makes them for the 4506.  Leather holsters for the SIG P220 or Beretta 92 will usually fit a 4506/1006 well.

Pistol, extra mag, 75 rds of premium defense ammo, and a gun case.

$550 for everything, price is firm and more than fair.  Will not ship.  No trades, need the cash.  Do not respond if you are prohibited from owning a firearm.  I reserve the right to withdraw this item from sale at any time or to refuse to do business with anyone I don't like.  Thanks.

title: For Sale/Trade:  WW2 Hungarian Mannlicher M1943 8mm Rifle
location: south side, chicago, illinois, Chicago, Illinois
postcontent:
Hello, I have a Hungarian Mannlicher M1943 rifle in 8mm. The rifle is in the original condition as it was recovered and taken home after the war. Rifle is chambered in the 8mm Mauser caliber. It has the Hungarian army shield stamp and the 43M marked on the receiver. Im not a history expert but what i do know is that these were made in Hungary prior to german occupation for their troops. Once Germany captured Hungary, the made the factory switch the rifle to 8mm and start using various Mauser parts on it such as the mag plate and stripper clips etc. at which time it got the 43M stamp. The action is very similar and very smooth as a Mauser but slightly different.  Most of these guns were stamped with nazi eagles etc. but some like this one was not and this makes it slightly more rare. Anyway, down to the nitty-gritty. Rifle action, bolt and mag plate, etc are all in really good shape for their age, only minor wear from use. The barrel and receiver are in good shape too but do show signs of blue wearing and minor cosmetic flaws such as tiny scratches or dings etc. but for being over 60 years old its in great shape. Id say blueing is about 80% or so, but im not appraising expert, thats just my opinion. The stock is in bad shape...its warped from age, and its missing the top handguard piece that mauser type rifles are known for. All metal is there such as sling swivels, butt plate and screws, screws etc. Screw heads are worn though, and bayonet mount is missing. Otherwise its a solid piece that does shoot and operate well. It could be restored with the addition of a new stock or used as a parts rifle as it is intact parts wise. Its a real piece of WW2 history that isnt very common from what i have seen/read. I just have no real use or desire for it and would like to sell/trade it to someone who does. Includes a box and a half of 8mm ammo. More pics available upon request. Contact me with any questions or offers........

Asking price:  $300.00

The shorter trigger system with integral hammer block and the extraction system are adapted from the P-3AT. Just like the P-11, the PF-9 will accept +P ammunition, however, not with continuous use.
The rear sight is a new design and is adjustable for windage with the supplied allen wrench as well as for elevation with the use of shims (not included). The included 7 round rectangular magazine is supplied with a finger extension base plate and numbered holes. The under barrel accessory rail shares the dimensions of the MIL-STD-1913 picatinny rail although there is only one locking notch in the forward position.
